When I was asked to sing at the @iamatheatre holiday fundraiser, I knew I wanted to bring something newish and Jewish to the mix. Not easy to find a beautiful Hannukah song! But I wanted to do a version of Al Hanissim, the prayer we sing on Hannukah thanking God for miracles… and miraculously I found a gorgeous melody by Israeli musician Efraim Markowtiz + put my own spin on it (including some English in the final verse). 

Happy Hannukah, happy holidays. Thanks for the miracles.

From the moment we met, I was in love with the mom I knew you were going to be- and you have exceeded all of my dreams. 

You’re my hero, our kids’ hero, and a hero to so many other moms you support with your wisdom and love. Our kids are growing up in the most loving and nurturing home, always adorably styled, every want and need thoughtfully provided for with your meticulous care. 

Everyone is always coming up to me to tell me how amazing you are — I’m happy to get to tell everyone myself today. You’re an amazing woman, mother, and person and our kids are just the luckiest to have you - they know it and so do I. I’m so glad we chose each other, my love. Happy Mothers Day.

Have you ever felt like you weren’t “allowed” to claim your Judaism? 

No one can take your identity from you. We all deserve to take up space, define our own narrative, and stand proud of who we are. 

One of my favorite parts of being Jewish is our values - of compassion, inclusivity, and loving-kindness. As a community, we need to do a much better job of walking the walk — there is room for EVERYONE in our tent. And if you feel like you aren’t welcome, I see you. Come inside.

First 24 hours away from our kiddos in literally YEARS so of course we beelined to Melville Winery in Lompoc on an absolutely beautiful summer afternoon. We had so many delicious pours (we came home with a bottle of the 2013 Chardonnay from their library reserve) and loved getting a behind-the-scenes look of where all the magic happens (Melville is one of very few California wineries to use solely estate-grown fruit for every one of their bottles!)

I’ve always loved Santa Rita Hills wines, and thanks to our tasting and tutelage at Melville (courtesy of Nicole!), now I really understand why! Thanks for having us, Melville! Until next time…

The good old days! When I was a college student at @uofpenn, I had such a loving and vibrant community of friends around me, centered around two of my greatest passions: music + shenanigans. Being part of this community gave me the strength and safety to be myself, to make mistakes and learn and grow, and to build bonds that last to this day. 

I would never have dreamed of facing the disturbing surge of Anti-Jewish hate that students on campuses are experiencing today. It is critical that we support Jewish students right now, across the country.

To that end, I’m partnering with the Jewish college students of @DailySchmooze in support of their #CampusReports campaign. By sharing their personal experiences on campus, they’re doing important, vulnerable work to combat hate and build community. Please give them a follow to show your support! #AlliesAgainstAntisemitism

Itai is 38. I’m 37. This could be me. 

Itai was visiting his parents in their home when terrorists invaded, brutally murdered his mother and father in front of him, and kidnapped him to live in fear and misery in a tunnel underground for 65 days and counting. Take a moment to put yourself in his place and think about what that nightmare would actually feel like, a hell that started October 7th that Itai has been living every second of every day since. 

I actually got the opportunity to speak with Itai’s cousins in LA. Their pleas to bring this kind and gentle soul back home are captured in a video on my grid. Please watch, listen, remember. 

I pray today, and every day, that Itai and the 170 innocent human beings still being held hostage are returned to their families (or what is left of them). We cannot forget them. 

#bringthemhome #bringthemhomenow #hannukah #prayer #peace #love

Ain’t no dinner like a Shabbat dinner! One of my favorite things about being a Jew is celebrating Shabbat every Friday, taking time out from whatever the hell is going on to just be with the people we love, eat delicious food, and feel some calm and  gratitude. Now more than ever, being in community with kindhearted people, both Jewish and not, feels so nourishing, so healing, so necessary. 

Thanks to @davidsuissajj for opening up his home - we’re all excited for Hen and Shanni’s new project (more to come!)
Wishing all of you a wonderful Shabbat of peace and love.
